##   GDS       0.808 0.192
##   TA/TO     0.590 0.410
##   Undefined 0.200 0.800

The cancellation rates based on market segment of the customer and the distribution channel the booking was made are quite interesting. For the market segment, the cancellation rates seem fairly consistent with the exception of Group bookings which have a cancellation rate nearly double the nearest segment (Online TA). Interestingly, when broken down into customer type, Group bookings have a much lower cancellation rate than the group market segment, a possible error is apparent in how the markets are categorized between these two measures (market segment vs customer type descriptions do not provide explanation in Kaggle). We see a similar scenario for the distribution sample, where corporate, direct, and GDS are all similar, but TA/TO (travel agents/tour operators) channel is nearly double that of any other channel excluding the undefined customers.

3.3 Deposit Type

deposit_cancel <- round(prop.table(table(hotels$deposit_type,
                                         hotels$is_canceled),1), 3) #Calculates cancellation rates by deposit type

plot(round(prop.table(table(hotels$deposit_type, hotels$is_canceled),1), 3),
     main="Cancellation by Deposit Type",
     ylab = "Cancellation",
     col=c("sky blue", "pink"))

#Graphs cancellation rates by deposit type

The cancellation rates for each deposit type is incredibly interesting. Among those with non-refundable deposits almost all of those customers ended up canceling their room, about 0.994. This made us doubt that the data was labeled incorrectly, but found in a Kaggle discussion post that the author of the paper, which the data set is from, addressed this issue: “…through analysis of the “Nonrefundable” (Deposit Type) canceled bookings in some Asiatic countries (Country) and from certain distribution channels (Distribution Channel and Agent), it is possible to understand why so many “Nonrefundable” bookings are canceled. These bookings are usually made through OTA using false or invalid credit card details. These bookings are issued as support for requests for visas to enter the country (a hotel booking is mandatory for applying for a Portuguese entry visa)." This is important information to consider when forecasting demand to make demand-management decisions.

From these pie charts we can see a notable difference between families who had kids and families who did not have kids when buying meals. The top meal choice of Bed & Breakfast did not change between groups, but the percentage bought did have a marked change. For the adults with kids, 85.4% bought the BB choice, while only 76.9% bought the BB choice. It seems that the adults with no kids group had a larger portion opt out of a meal choice (SC with 9.5% and Undefined with 1%) than the group of adults that had kids. This could show that the adults without kids are able to get meals in any means they see necessary, while the adults with kids would probably want convenience over everything while having more mouth to feed.

5 Conclusion

5.1 Insights

  • Customers who were planning to stay in the city hotels tended to cancel bookings more than those planning to stay in the resort hotels.

  • Majority of customers who canceled their bookings chose non-refundable options.

  • Both types of hotels would need to have more Type A rooms, which is the most sought-after room type among all customers.

  • Customers with children tend to have breakfast options more than customers who do not.

  • Customers booked through agents pay more on average, but the cancellation rate is also high.

  • The longer the lead time, the more likely customers are to cancel it.

  • Although city hotels have more bookings, they also tend to have more cancellations.

5.2 Business Implication

  • Hotels have insight into customers’ meal preferences and room preferences, which will help hotels consider package options and conduct events to attract customers to generate more revenue.

  • Resort hotels tend to have less bookings than city hotels, so they will need to work on their marketing. This under the assumption that both hotel types have the same capacity.

  • Hotels can conduct additional research, such as a TA/TO survey, to gain insight into why customers who booked a room through agents have a higher cancellation rate. It will help them analyze the booking rates and potential income.

  • Most customers travel alone or in pairs so the hotels could advertise in ways that attract couples as well as business travelers.

  • City hotels could sell more non-refundable bookings during peak times or apply stricter refund policies to prevent revenue loss from the cancellations.

  • Since June-August happens to be the busiest months, hotels should target more customers during this time by providing more value package options to maximize the revenue than in the other months.
